full_text: @RyanSkursky On good months, do higher lump sum payments, on bad months, roll it back. Set a date for when you'd like to have it paid off by, and aim for that, but be understanding if it's a moving target (especially given current world events/the economy).
full_text(utf-8): b"@RyanSkursky On good months, do higher lump sum payments, on bad months, roll it back. Set a date for when you'd like to have it paid off by, and aim for that, but be understanding if it's a moving target (especially given current world events/the economy)."

full_text:
@RyanSkursky My last piece of advice is to ignore the minimum payments banks set up for you (those will keep you shackled for years), and setup your own payment plan.

Keep it fluid (the uncertainty of freelancing complicates budgets), but have a minimum amount to throw at it each month.
full_text(utf-8): b'@RyanSkursky My last piece of advice is to ignore the minimum payments banks set up for you (those will keep you shackled for years), and setup your own payment plan.\n\nKeep it fluid (the uncertainty of freelancing complicates budgets), but have a minimum amount to throw at it each month.'

full_text:
@RyanSkursky (TD often has "3.99% for a year" offers, that I'll take advantage of when I know I'm going to be buying gear.)

On the note of paying debts: look into the snowball & avalanche methods, they're neat tricks for paying off debts (I used the avalanche method).

full_text: @RyanSkursky That said! Look into getting a line of credit. If you can get approved, you can consolidate any CC debt you do have at a much lower rate, and invest in gear at a lower rate as well. LOC are usually around 8-10% vs the 20% that CCs have, & sometimes you can lock in to lower rates.

This was a big learn for me last year. Experienced major burnout & an existential crisis.
